{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.36,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57843"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents with a one day history of constant lower abdominal pain and fever. On examination he has a temperature of 38.2\u00b0C and there is tenderness in the left iliac fossa. A provisional diagnosis of acute diverticulitis is made.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the gold-standard investigation for establishing the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Barium enema","Colonoscopy","CT scan abdomen and pelvis","MRI of the abdomen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing diverticulitis. It provides detailed images that can confirm the presence of diverticula, inflammation, and complications such as abscesses or perforation. Here is an example, showing an abscess cavity (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended during an acute episode of diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation. It may be used after the acute episode has resolved to assess the extent of diverticular disease (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to evaluate abdominal pain but is less sensitive and specific than CT for diagnosing diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for diagnosing diverticulitis due to its higher cost and limited availability compared to CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarium enema\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated method for diagnosing diverticulitis and is not commonly used in current practice due to the risk of perforation and the availability of more accurate imaging techniques (Image 3).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is the gold standard for diagnosing diverticulitis.","Diverticulitis typically presents with left lower quadrant pain, fever, and changes in bowel habits.","Colonoscopy is not recommended during an acute episode of diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation."],"references":["Destigter KK, Keating DP. Imaging update: acute colonic diverticulitis. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2009 Aug;22(3):147-55. doi: 10.1055/s-0029-1236158. PMID: 20676257; PMCID: PMC2780264.","Hawkins AT, Wise PE, Chan T, Lee JT, Glyn T, Wood V, Eglinton T, Frizelle F, Khan A, Hall J, Ilyas MIM, Michailidou M, Nfonsam VN, Cowan ML, Williams J, Steele SR, Alavi K, Ellis CT, Collins D, Winter DC, Zaghiyan K, Gallo G, Carvello M, Spinelli A, Lightner AL. Diverticulitis: An Update From the Age Old Paradigm. Curr Probl Surg. 2020 Oct;57(10):100862. doi: 10.1016/j.cpsurg.2020.100862. Epub 2020 Jul 18. PMID: 33077029; PMCID: PMC7575828.","Tursi A. A critical appraisal of advances in the diagnosis of diverticular disease. Expert Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2018 Aug;12(8):791-796. doi: 10.1080/17474124.2018.1487288. Epub 2018 Jun 19. PMID: 29888630.","Hawkins AT, Wise PE, Chan T, Lee JT, Glyn T, Wood V, Eglinton T, Frizelle F, Khan A, Hall J, Ilyas MIM, Michailidou M, Nfonsam VN, Cowan ML, Williams J, Steele SR, Alavi K, Ellis CT, Collins D, Winter DC, Zaghiyan K, Gallo G, Carvello M, Spinelli A, Lightner AL. Diverticulitis: An Update From the Age Old Paradigm. Curr Probl Surg. 2020 Oct;57(10):100862. doi: 10.1016/j.cpsurg.2020.100862. Epub 2020 Jul 18. PMID: 33077029; PMCID: PMC7575828."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57843"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21348"},{"type":"media","id":"21349"},{"type":"media","id":"21350"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21348"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MJ9FqF8R06c17JdC5KCWV2iYQNqOm3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MJ9FqF8R06c17JdC5KCWV2iYQNqOm3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":842,"height":586}},{"type":"media","id":"21349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21349"},"attrib